<h3>Course Goals</h3>

The primary goal of the course is <b>mathematical intellectual
  growth</b>. This involves understanding mathematical concepts,
  analysis and problem solving, and clear, concise communication.
Achievement of course goals requires desire for learning, willingness to
  work hard, time, and persistence.

<p>

<i>Learning objectives</i> (also called <i>student learning
  outcomes</i>) are "skills, competencies, and abilities
students demonstrate in the course, and what knowledge students acquire
in the course" (definition taken from <i>Elements of Course Syllabi</i>
from the Office of the Associate Dean of Academic Affairs). Students who desire to learn, work hard, spend at least
two hours on homework outside of class for each hour in class, and
persist until they master each topic, will
<ul>
<li>demonstrate <b>understanding of mathematical concepts</b>,
<li>demonstrate skill in <b>analysis and problem solving</b>, and
<li>demonstrate skill in <b>clear, concise communication</b> (for courses numbered
  200 and higher), and
<li>demonstrate <b>mastery of the course material</b> at a satisfactory
  level (grade `C') or higher.
</ul>

<p>

